   "source": [
    "# NOTE on Variables\n",
    "*There are two different variable sets.  The first are available from the HCRIS dataset.  The second are engineered from the available data.\n",
    "\n",
    "## RAW Available Variables\n",
    "\n",
    "🏥 Category A: Clinical Volume & Utilization\n",
    "These variables represent the Operational Denominators. In a bankruptcy model, they are used to detect \"Operational De-coupling\"—where the physical reality of the hospital (patients and beds) no longer aligns with the financial reporting.\n",
    "\n",
    "| Variable Name        | HCRIS Source (Wkst, Line, Col) | Definition | Utility for Bankruptcy & Distress Modeling |\n",
    "|----------------------|--------------------------------|------------|--------------------------------------------|\n",
    "| licensed_beds | S300001, 01400, 00200 | Total beds the facility is state-licensed to operate. | Capacity baseline for overhead ratios. High bed counts with low utilization create fixed-cost strain that accelerates insolvency. |\n",
    "| total_patient_days | S300001, 01400, 00800 | Cumulative days spent by all inpatients in the facility. | Denominator for \"Cost per Day\" anomalies. Volume decline without cost compression signals distress. |\n",
    "| total_discharges | S300001, 01400, 01500 | Total number of patients released after an inpatient stay. | Primary throughput metric for \"Revenue per Discharge.\" Sharp YoY declines often precede margin collapse. |\n",
    "| medicare_discharges | S300001, 00100, 01300 | Discharges for Title XVIII (Medicare) patients. | Medicare-specific volume exposure. High federal dependence increases reimbursement and clawback risk. |\n",
    "| outpatient_visits | S300001, 00100, 00300 | Total outpatient encounters (clinics, surgery, etc.). | Measures the \"Outpatient Pivot\" strategy. Sudden spikes can indicate survival-driven volume shifting. |\n",
    "| er_visits_ipps | S300002, 01300, 00200 | ED visits (standard IPPS form). | Inconsistent ED reporting across forms can signal operational shifts—IPPS visits reflect standard reporting. |\n",
    "| er_visits_alt | S300004, 01300, 00100 | ED visits (alternate form). | Alternate form ED visits can emerge in rural or special cases—use max of IPPS or alt to avoid double-counting. |\n",
    "| swing_bed_days | S300003, 00500, 00600 | Days for patients transitioning between acute and SNF care. | High-margin post-acute volume. Critical for rural and CAH financial stability. |\n",
    "\n",
    "💰 Category B: Revenue Integrity & Billing\n",
    "These fields track the flow from \"Sticker Price\" (Gross) to \"Actual Cash\" (Net). Discrepancies here are the primary indicators of aggressive revenue recognition and subsidy dependency.\n",
    "\n",
    "| Variable Name        | HCRIS Source (Wkst, Line, Col) | Definition | Utility for Bankruptcy & Distress Modeling |\n",
    "|----------------------|--------------------------------|------------|--------------------------------------------|\n",
    "| gross_patient_revenue | G300000, 00100, 00100 | Total billings at full established rates (Sticker Price). | Inflation Marker: Distressed hospitals often spike gross rates to make contractual allowances appear as charitable discounts. |\n",
    "| contractual_allowances | G300000, 00200, 00100 | Difference between gross billings and what payers actually pay. | Payer Friction: A sudden rise indicates insurers rejecting claims or weakening hospital negotiating leverage. |\n",
    "| net_patient_revenue | G300000, 00300, 00100 | Actual realized income from patient care (Gross minus Allowances). | Core Vitality: If this trends down while total charges rise, the hospital is billing into the void. |\n",
    "| other_operating_rev | G300000, 02500, 00100 | Revenue from non-patient sources (cafeteria, parking, gift shop). | Survival Pivot: Failing hospitals often rely on non-clinical revenue to offset patient-care losses. |\n",
    "| total_charges | G200000, 02800, 00300 | Sum of all hospital charges. | CCR Denominator: Used to compute cost-to-charge ratios and detect pricing inflation strategies. |\n",
    "| medicare_charges | D00A182, 20000, 00200 | Charges specifically attributed to Medicare patients. | Federal Exposure: Measures dependence on federally reimbursed patient volume. |\n",
    "| cah_dsh_payment | E30A185, 03300, 00100 | CAH or small hospital DSH payments. | Small rural lifeline: CAHs and smaller facilities rely heavily on these DSH payments to stay afloat. |\n",
    "| dsh_payment_amt | E000001, 03300, 00100 | Disproportionate Share Hospital (DSH) subsidy payments. | Safety Net Lifeline: Critical subsidy stream for hospitals serving low-income populations. |\n",
    "| ipps_payments | E10A181, 00100, 00200 | Direct DRG payments for inpatient stays. | Complexity Proxy: Changes relative to revenue can signal coding or case-mix shifts. |\n",
    "| interim_payments | E10A181, 00400, 00200 | Payments received during the year based on estimated costs. | Liquidity Bridge: High interim payments create reconciliation risk at settlement. |\n",
    "| ime_payment_amt | E30A197, 02900, 00100 | Indirect Medical Education payments for teaching hospitals. | Subsidy Dependency: Heavy reliance suggests underlying margins are weak. |\n",
    "| hitech_payment_amt | E00A18A, 06400, 00100 | EHR adoption incentive payments. | One-time windfall payments that historically masked operational weakness. |\n",
    "| final_settlement | E00A18A, 07400, 00100 | Final reconciliation payment owed to or from CMS. | Settlement Shock: Large repayments can trigger sudden liquidity crises. |\n",
    "\n",
    "📉 Category C: Cost Structure & Operating Expense\n",
    "These variables track where hospital resources are spent. The key analytic tension appears when cost growth diverges from patient volume.\n",
    "\n",
    "| Variable Name        | HCRIS Source (Wkst, Line, Col) | Definition | Utility for Bankruptcy & Distress Modeling |\n",
    "|----------------------|--------------------------------|------------|--------------------------------------------|\n",
    "| total_operating_exp | G300000, 00400, 00100 | Total costs associated with hospital operations. | Efficiency Floor: If this remains static while patient volume falls, the hospital faces severe operating leverage risk. |\n",
    "| net_income | G300000, 02900, 00100 | Net surplus or deficit after expenses. | Bottom-Line Signal: Persistent losses strongly predict insolvency or acquisition. |\n",
    "| total_routine_costs | B000001, 03000, 02600 | Standard inpatient room and nursing costs. | Fixed Cost Baseline: High values relative to patient days indicate underutilization. |\n",
    "| drug_costs | A000000, 07300, 00700 | Direct pharmaceutical expenses. | Supply Inflation Signal: Rapid growth suggests cost control failures or vendor risk. |\n",
    "| medical_supply_costs | A000000, 07100, 00700 | Direct medical supply expenditures. | Quality Tradeoff Indicator: Sudden declines may reflect cost cutting impacting care quality. |\n",
    "| admin_general_costs | A000000, 00500, 00700 | Administrative and management costs. | Overhead Bloat Index: High values relative to revenue signal governance inefficiency. |\n",
    "| maintenance_repairs | A000000, 00600, 00700 | Physical plant maintenance costs. | Deferred Maintenance Warning: Distressed hospitals often underfund maintenance. |\n",
    "| labor_delivery_costs | A000000, 05200, 00700 | Labor and delivery department costs. | Service Line Sustainability: Used to identify departments becoming structural loss leaders. |\n",
    "| radiology_diagnostic | A000000, 05400, 00700 | Diagnostic radiology costs. | Imaging Dependency Indicator: Excessive reliance increases audit vulnerability. |\n",
    "| laboratory_costs | A000000, 06000, 00700 | Clinical laboratory service costs. | Volume Integrity: Lab costs should correlate tightly with patient encounters. |\n",
    "\n",
    "👥 Category D: Labor & Human Capital\n",
    "These variables allow the VAE to detect \"Labor Tension\"—the point where clinical staffing levels become dangerously low relative to patient volume or where executive/physician pay remains high despite falling margins.\n",
    "\n",
    "| Variable Name        | HCRIS Source (Wkst, Line, Col) | Definition | Utility for Bankruptcy & Distress Modeling |\n",
    "|----------------------|--------------------------------|------------|--------------------------------------------|\n",
    "| total_salaries | A000000, 20000, 00100 | Total cash compensation paid to all hospital employees. | The Efficiency Baseline: Used to calculate revenue per employee. A spike in salaries without volume growth indicates poor management or payroll padding. |\n",
    "| total_comp_salben | A000000, 20000, 00200 | Total salaries plus benefits combined. | Benefit Compression Signal: Used to detect when benefits are cut before salaries in distress. |\n",
    "| total_ftes | S300001, 02700, 01000 | Full-Time Equivalents (total hours divided by standard work week). | The Capacity Anchor: When FTEs stay high while discharges fall, the hospital is over-staffed for its reality, leading to rapid equity depletion. |\n",
    "| intern_resident_ftes | S300001, 02700, 00900 | Number of training doctors on staff. | Subsidized Labor: Teaching hospitals use residents as low-cost labor subsidized by CMS. |\n",
    "| physician_comp_total | A820010, 20000, 00400 | Total compensation specifically for physicians. | Insider Extracting: In some distress scenarios, physician-owners extract high compensation even as liquidity deteriorates. |\n",
    "| physician_rce_limit | A820010, 20000, 00900 | CMS Reasonable Compensation Equivalent cap. | Regulatory Risk: Compensation above this limit is not reimbursable—triggers audit risk. |\n",
    "| budgeted_ftes | S300001, 02800, 00800 | Budgeted full-time equivalents for staff. | Staffing Gap: Comparing actual FTEs to budgeted can highlight operational strain or underutilization. |\n",
    "\n",
    "🏛️ Category E: Capital Structure, Assets & Solvency\n",
    "These variables allow the VAE to define the \"Solvency Envelope.\" Anomalies here represent technical insolvency—where the hospital’s obligations exceed its resources, or where assets are being \"hollowed out\" to cover operational losses.\n",
    "\n",
    "| Variable Name        | HCRIS Source (Wkst, Line, Col) | Definition | Utility for Bankruptcy & Distress Modeling |\n",
    "|----------------------|--------------------------------|------------|--------------------------------------------|\n",
    "| total_assets | G000000, 03600, 00100 | The sum of all resources owned (Cash, AR, Fixed Assets). | The Denominator: Used for Return on Assets (ROA) and leverage ratios. A shrinking asset base is the hallmark of a liquidating hospital. |\n",
    "| total_liabilities | G000000, 05100, 00100 | All debts and obligations owed by the hospital. | Insolvency Marker: When this exceeds total_assets, the hospital is technically insolvent. This is a primary VAE trigger for bankruptcy risk. |\n",
    "| current_assets | G000000, 01100, 00100 | Cash and assets expected to be converted to cash within one year. | Working Capital: The fuel for operations. A rapid drop here indicates a hospital is about to run out of money to pay staff. |\n",
    "| current_liabilities | G000000, 04400, 00100 | Debts due within one year (AP, short-term notes). | The Liquidity Trap: Used for the Current Ratio. If this rises while current_assets falls, the liquidity trap flag is triggered. |\n",
    "| cash_ending | G000000, 00100, 00100 | Actual cash and cash equivalents on hand at year-end. | Survival Metric: The numerator for Days Cash on Hand. This is the single most volatile predictor of immediate closure. |\n",
    "| inventory | G000000, 00700, 00100 | Value of medical supplies, drugs, and equipment on hand. | Inventory Bloat or Shortage: Distressed hospitals may liquidate or understock inventory to raise cash, harming clinical quality. |\n",
    "| fixed_assets_net | G000000, 03100, 00100 | Value of land, buildings, and equipment after depreciation. | Collateral Value: Represents what the hospital is worth to lenders. Low value limits refinancing options. |\n",
    "| accumulated_depr | G000000, 03000, 00100 | Total depreciation taken on all fixed assets to date. | Capital Age: High accumulated depreciation relative to fixed_assets_net indicates an aging facility nearing capital crisis. |\n",
    "| long_term_debt | G000000, 04600, 00100 | Mortgages, bonds, and notes due after one year. | Solvency Anchor: High long-term debt creates substantial interest expense. If revenue falls while this remains high, bankruptcy risk escalates. |\n",
    "| equity_unrestricted | G000000, 05200, 00100 | Cumulative net worth or fund balance of the entity. | The Safety Buffer: Represents the hospital's ability to absorb losses. Once negative, the facility is operating on borrowed time. |\n",
    "| total_investments | G000000, 00200, 00100 | Marketable securities or non-operating investments. | Non-Operating Hedge: Sudden liquidation of this account signals operational emergency. |\n",
    "| other_assets_misc | G000000, 03200, 00100 | Miscellaneous assets not categorized elsewhere. | The Hidey-Hole: Large or growing balances here are forensic targets for earnings management or hidden related-party transfers. |\n",
    "\n",
    "🚩 Category F: Uncompensated Care & Audit Signals\n",
    "These variables are high-weight inputs for forensic models. Outliers here often correlate with hospitals that are either under extreme financial duress or are engaging in aggressive \"Cost Report Engineering\" to stave off insolvency.\n",
    "\n",
    "| Variable Name        | HCRIS Source (Wkst, Line, Col) | Definition | Utility for Bankruptcy & Distress Modeling |\n",
    "|----------------------|--------------------------------|------------|--------------------------------------------|\n",
    "| charity_care_cost | S100000, 02300, 00100 | The actual cost of care provided to patients who meet the facility’s indigency policy. | Non-Profit Integrity: If this drops significantly while maintaining tax-exempt status, it signals a shift toward profit maximization over mission, often preceding restructuring. |\n",
    "| bad_debt_cost | S100000, 02900, 00100 | The cost of care for patients who were expected to pay but did not. | Payer Mix Volatility: High bad debt directly drains liquidity. A sudden spike indicates local economic stress or failure in revenue cycle management. |\n",
    "| total_uncomp_care | S100000, 03000, 00100 | The sum of Charity Care and Bad Debt. | The Safety-Net Burden: Primary driver for DSH payments. High uncompensated care with low subsidies creates a financial death spiral. |\n",
    "| home_office_adj | A810000, 00500, 00400 | Adjustments for costs incurred by a parent organization or home office. | Profit Siphoning Signal: High allocations to a loss-making hospital suggest the parent entity is extracting value while weakening the facility. |\n",
    "| overhead_stepdown_total | B000001, 20200, 00000 | Final total after sequential allocation of overhead to clinical centers. | Allocation Integrity: Used to verify that the step-down allocation preserved total costs. Inconsistencies suggest technical error or intentional manipulation. |\n",
    "\n",
    "🕵️ Category G: The \"Paper Trail\" & Settlement Risk\n",
    "These variables identify when a hospital is \"borrowing\" from the future to pay for today.\n",
    "\n",
    "| Variable Name        | HCRIS Source (Wkst, Line, Col) | Definition | Utility for Bankruptcy & Distress Modeling |\n",
    "|----------------------|--------------------------------|------------|--------------------------------------------|\n",
    "| accounts_receivable | G000000, 00400, 00100 | Net patient accounts receivable. | The A/R Trap: If accounts receivable grows while volume declines, the hospital may be recognizing revenue that is unlikely to be collected. |\n",
    "| accounts_payable | G000000, 03700, 00100 | Amounts owed to vendors and suppliers. | Vendor Pressure Signal: A spike indicates the hospital is delaying payments to preserve cash, often a precursor to supply disruption. |\n",
    "| due_from_medicare | G000000, 00500, 00100 | Amount owed from Medicare (if interim payments exceeded costs). | Positive balance here suggests reliance on advance Medicare funding, which can reverse if settlement goes negative. |\n",
    "| due_to_medicare | G000000, 04100, 00100 | Excess interim payments owed back to CMS. | The Clawback Liability: A fixed obligation where CMS recoups overpayments, potentially triggering sudden liquidity collapse. |\n",
    "| notes_receivable | G000000, 00600, 00100 | Notes receivable from related parties or others. | Flag for Related-Party Risk: Convert to a binary indicator—presence suggests financial engineering or dependency on external promises. |\n",
    "| other_current_liab | G000000, 04200, 00100 | Miscellaneous other current liabilities. | Hidden Current Obligations: Convert to binary flag—can indicate undisclosed short-term liabilities that erode liquidity. |\n",
    "\n",
    "🏷️ Category: Basic Identity\n",
    "These variables serve as the unique keys for joining your HCRIS data with external forensic datasets like the Census Bureau (County poverty levels), HRSA (Medically Underserved Areas), or AHA (American Hospital Association) membership files.\n",
    "\n",
    "| Variable Name | HCRIS Source (Wkst, Line, Col) | Definition | Utility for Bankruptcy & Distress Modeling |\n",
    "|---------------|--------------------------------|------------|--------------------------------------------|\n",
    "| street_addr | S200001, 00100, 00100 | The physical street address of the facility. | Real Estate Context: Distinguishes high-value urban facilities from remote rural properties, affecting fixed-asset resale value in liquidation scenarios. |\n",
    "| city | S200001, 00200, 00100 | The city where the hospital is located. | Market Concentration: Helps identify sole community providers that may receive federal protection or supplemental funding. |\n",
    "| state | S200001, 00200, 00200 | Two-letter state abbreviation. | Regulatory Proxy: States differ in Medicaid reimbursement rates, expansion status, and Certificate of Need laws, shaping the hospital’s competitive and funding environment. |\n",
    "| zip_code | S200001, 00200, 00300 | Five-digit USPS postal code. | Demographic Mapping: Primary join key for linking zip-level income, poverty, and insurance coverage data to forecast bad debt exposure. |\n",
    "| county | S200001, 00200, 00400 | County of hospital operation. | Economic Engine: Enables integration of county unemployment and economic indicators, leading predictors of self-pay and uncompensated care spikes. |\n",
    "| hospital_name | S200001, 00300, 00100 | Legal name of the reporting hospital entity. | Entity Tracking: Essential for matching closures, mergers, acquisitions, and bankruptcy filings to the financial panel. |\n",
    "\n",
    "🏗️ Category: Structural Peer Grouping\n",
    "These variables allow the model to cluster hospitals into \"peer cohorts\" so anomaly detection is performed relative to a meaningful operational baseline.\n",
    "\n",
    "| Variable Name | HCRIS Source (Wkst, Line, Col) | Definition | Utility for Bankruptcy & Distress Modeling |\n",
    "|---------------|--------------------------------|------------|--------------------------------------------|\n",
    "| control_type_code | S200001, 02100, 00100 | Ownership classification (e.g., Voluntary Non-Profit, Government, Proprietary For-Profit). | Profit Motive Anchor: For-profits have higher bankruptcy exit potential, while non-profits may rely on endowments or subsidies that temporarily conceal distress. |\n",
    "| urban_rural_status | S200001, 00300, 00600 | Geographic designation indicating urban or rural location. | Volume Expectation: Rural hospitals naturally operate at lower volume; urban hospitals with rural-level utilization represent strong distress signals. |\n",
    "| is_teaching | S200001, 05600, 00100 | Indicates whether the hospital operates an approved residency training program. | Cost Structure Justification: Teaching hospitals carry higher administrative and salary costs due to education and supervision mandates. |\n",
    "| is_cah | S200001, 10500, 00100 | Critical Access Hospital designation indicator. | Reimbursement Protection: CAHs receive cost-based reimbursement; if a CAH remains unprofitable, distress risk is severe despite structural subsidy support. |\n",
    "| is_chain | S200001, 14000, 00100 | Indicates whether the hospital belongs to a multi-hospital system. | Systemic Contagion: Chain membership may mask standalone financial distress through parent subsidies or cross-subsidization. |\n",
    "## ENGINEERED Variables\n",
    "\n",
    "🧪 Category 1: Clinical & Operational Intensity\n",
    "These ratios detect \"Operational De-coupling\"—when a hospital's financial output begins to drift away from its clinical reality.\n",
    "| Variable Name | Formula / Definition | Utility for Bankruptcy & Distress Modeling |\n",
    "|---------------|----------------------|--------------------------------------------|\n",
    "| cmi_proxy | Total Ancillary Costs / Total Routine Costs | Complexity Anchor: Serves as a proxy for Case Mix Index (CMI). A high ratio suggests intensive service lines (Surgery, ICU). A declining ratio indicates loss of high-margin complex cases to competitors. |\n",
    "| forensic_efficiency | Net Revenue / (Discharges * CMI Proxy) | The Revenue per Unit Metric: Measures revenue per complexity-adjusted discharge. Extreme high values suggest potential upcoding; extreme low values indicate revenue capture failure. |\n",
    "| labor_intensity | Total Salaries / Total Operating Expense | Fixed Cost Rigidity: Labor is the most difficult cost to reduce. Ratios above 60% imply minimal operating flexibility and high bankruptcy sensitivity to volume shocks. |\n",
    "| outpatient_pivot | Outpatient Visits / Total Discharges | Structural Transformation: Captures the shift from inpatient beds to outpatient clinics. A rapid increase may signal strategic adaptation or the quiet shutdown of inpatient capacity. |\n",
    "\n",
    "💰 Category 2: Revenue Integrity & Billing Aggression\n",
    "These variables track the gap between what a hospital claims it is worth (Gross Charges) and what the market actually pays (Net Revenue).\n",
    "| Variable Name | Formula / Definition | Utility for Bankruptcy & Distress Modeling |\n",
    "|---------------|----------------------|--------------------------------------------|\n",
    "| ccr | Total Operating Exp / Total Gross Charges | The Cost-to-Charge Ratio: Measures how much cost exists in each dollar billed. A very low CCR (e.g., < 0.15) signals aggressive markup behavior. If CCR falls while margins remain weak, pricing power is deteriorating. |\n",
    "| collection_efficiency | Net Patient Rev / Gross Patient Rev | Revenue Quality: The realization rate of billed revenue. A declining ratio indicates claim denials, payer friction, or inability to collect, and is a leading indicator of cash-flow instability. |\n",
    "| medicare_dependency | Medicare Charges / Total Gross Charges | Concentration Risk: Captures reliance on federal reimbursement. High dependency ties solvency directly to Medicare rate changes and audit exposure. |\n",
    "| charity_commitment | Charity Care Cost / Total Operating Exp | Mission vs. Margin: Tracks resources allocated to indigent care. In financial distress, hospitals may cut this to preserve liquidity, risking reputational and regulatory consequences. |\n",
    "\n",
    "🏛️ Category 3: Liquidity, Solvency & Capital Age\n",
    "These variables track the hospital's ability to meet its immediate obligations and the long-term sustainability of its physical plant.\n",
    "| Variable Name | Formula / Definition | Utility for Bankruptcy & Distress Modeling |\n",
    "|---------------|----------------------|--------------------------------------------|\n",
    "| operating_margin | (Operating Revenue - Operating Expense) / Operating Revenue | Core Performance: Measures profitability of primary operations. A negative value means the hospital loses money on its core clinical mission. |\n",
    "| total_margin | Net Income / Total Revenue | Bottom Line Truth: Includes non-operating items (investments, donations). If materially higher than operating_margin, the hospital is being supported by external funding rather than clinical performance. |\n",
    "| return_on_assets | Net Income / Total Assets | Asset Productivity: Measures how efficiently capital assets generate earnings. A declining ROA signals underperforming or idle capital. |\n",
    "| current_ratio | Current Assets / Current Liabilities | Short-Term Survival: A ratio below 1.0 indicates insufficient liquidity to meet near-term obligations, signaling immediate solvency stress. |\n",
    "| equity_financing | (Total Assets - Total Liabilities) / Total Assets | Solvency Buffer: Represents the share of assets financed by equity. Values near zero or negative indicate heavy leverage and technical insolvency risk. |\n",
    "| days_cash_on_hand | Cash / (Operating Expense / 365) | The Survival Clock: The most critical short-run bankruptcy indicator. Values below 15 days represent acute liquidity vulnerability. |\n",
    "| capital_age_index | Accumulated Depreciation / (Fixed Assets + Accumulated Depreciation) | The Decay Factor: High values (e.g., >0.85) suggest an aging facility with elevated maintenance risk and declining competitive position. |\n",
    "\n",
    "🚩 Category 4: Forensic Risk & Distress (The Death Spiral)\n",
    "These variables identify the exact moment a hospital loses its ability to function as a going concern.\n",
    "| Variable Name | Formula / Definition | Utility for Bankruptcy & Distress Modeling |\n",
    "|---------------|----------------------|--------------------------------------------|\n",
    "| is_technically_insolvent | Total Liabilities > Total Assets | The Equity Floor: Binary flag (0/1). When 1, the hospital has negative net worth and is operating on creditor tolerance. |\n",
    "| liquidity_trap | Current Ratio < 1.0 | The Working Capital Crisis: Binary flag indicating short-term obligations exceed liquid resources. This is the mathematical definition of inability to meet near-term bills. |\n",
    "| cash_exhaustion | Days Cash on Hand < 15 | The Payroll Panic: Binary flag. Below 15 days represents acute liquidity emergency; a single delayed reimbursement can trigger default. |\n",
    "| admin_load | Admin General Costs / Total Operating Exp | The Administrative Load Metric: Measures the share of operating costs devoted to administration rather than clinical care. Rising admin_load during financial deterioration suggests structural imbalance. |\n",
    "| bankruptcy_proxy_score | is_technically_insolvent + liquidity_trap + cash_exhaustion | The Composite Risk Index: A 0–3 scale. A value of 3 indicates simultaneous insolvency, illiquidity, and cash exhaustion. |\n",
    "| is_terminal | bankruptcy_proxy_score >= 2 | The Terminal Classification: Identifies facilities in severe distress. In VAE training, these records represent the extreme-risk cluster that should separate from stable peers. |\n",
    "\n",
    "🔬 Category 5: Departmental Fraud Vectors\n",
    "These variables isolate specific cost centers that are historically associated with unbundling, \"ghost billing,\" and unnecessary diagnostic utilization.\n",
    "| Variable Name | Formula / Definition | Utility for Bankruptcy & Distress Modeling |\n",
    "|---------------|----------------------|--------------------------------------------|\n",
    "| high_risk_diagnostic_weight | (Laboratory Costs + Radiology Costs) / Total Ancillary Costs | Diagnostic Churn Indicator: Measures concentration of spending in high-risk diagnostic departments. If this ratio is an outlier relative to cmi_proxy, it suggests potential over-utilization of tests to inflate revenue. |\n",
    "\n",
    "📉 Category 6: The \"Cash-Flow Velocity\" Tensions\n",
    "| Variable Name | Formula / Definition | Utility for Bankruptcy & Distress |\n",
    "|---------------|----------------------|------------------------------------|\n",
    "| ar_velocity | Accounts Receivable / (Net Patient Revenue / 365) | Days in A/R: Measures how many days of revenue remain uncollected. A rapidly rising value is a leading indicator of revenue cycle breakdown or aggressive revenue recognition. |\n",
    "| ap_lag | Accounts Payable / (Total Operating Exp / 365) | Days in A/P: Measures how long the hospital delays vendor payments. Values exceeding 60–90 days signal severe liquidity stress and risk of supply disruption. |\n",
    "| asset_turnover | Net Patient Revenue / Total Assets | Efficiency of Scale: Indicates how effectively assets generate revenue. A declining ratio suggests underutilized capital and deteriorating operational efficiency. |\n",
    "\n",
    "🛑 Category 7: The \"Manipulation\" Flags\n",
    "These are the \"Smoke\" before the \"Fire.\"\n",
    "| Variable Name | Formula / Definition | Utility for Bankruptcy & Distress |\n",
    "|---------------|----------------------|------------------------------------|\n",
    "| revenue_per_discharge | Net Patient Revenue / Total Discharges | Billing Density: If this rises significantly (e.g., 20%) while cmi_proxy remains flat, it suggests potential upcoding to offset declining volume. |\n",
    "| subsidy_intensity | (DSH + IME + GME) / Net Patient Revenue | Government Life-Support Ratio: Values above 0.30 indicate heavy reliance on federal subsidy streams. Policy shifts or audit exposure can rapidly destabilize solvency. |\n",
    "| related_party_leverage | home_office_adj / Equity_Unrestricted | The Siphon Ratio: Measures the extent to which parent-level allocations consume the hospital’s net worth. High values indicate structural extraction risk. |\n",
    "\n",
    "📈 Category 8: Temporal Velocity (YoY Momentum)\n",
    "These engineered variables capture the \"First Derivative\" of hospital health—the rate of change across volume, efficiency, and solvency.\n",
    "| Variable Name | Formula / Logic | Utility for Bankruptcy & Distress Modeling |\n",
    "|---------------|-----------------|--------------------------------------------|\n",
    "| pct_change_volume | (Vol_t - Vol_t-1) / Vol_t-1 | Market Abandonment: Tracks percent change in Discharges or ER Visits. A sustained double-digit decline represents a Discharge Cliff that often precedes bankruptcy. |\n",
    "| delta_operating_margin | Margin_t - Margin_t-1 | Profitability Erosion: Measures the speed of core mission deterioration. A negative delta for three consecutive years signals a terminal financial trajectory. |\n",
    "| delta_days_cash | DaysCash_t - DaysCash_t-1 | The Burn Rate: Captures how quickly liquidity runway is shrinking. This is one of the most sensitive predictors of imminent payable crises. |\n",
    "| delta_collection_eff | CollEff_t - CollEff_t-1 | Revenue Cycle Decay: A declining value with stable volume indicates weakening payer collection capacity, a hidden insolvency signal. |\n",
    "| delta_ar_velocity | AR_Days_t - AR_Days_t-1 | A/R Expansion Signal: Rising values indicate revenue recognition outpacing cash realization, suggesting phantom revenue risk. |\n",
    "| delta_ap_lag | AP_Days_t - AP_Days_t-1 | Vendor Pressure Escalation: Positive changes indicate increasing payment delays to suppliers, often a late-stage distress indicator. |\n",
    "| delta_capital_age | CapAge_t - CapAge_t-1 | Infrastructure Deterioration: A rapid increase implies halted reinvestment and deferred maintenance to preserve liquidity. |\n",
    "| delta_admin_load | Admin%_t - Admin%_t-1 | Administrative Drift: Rising administrative burden during declining margins suggests structural imbalance and governance risk. |\n",
    "\n",
    "🧠 Category 9: Forensic Momentum & Logic Signals\n",
    "These binary and ratio-based signals identify specific patterns of \"Distress Behavior\"—distinguishing between a hospital that is simply in a poor market and one that is being \"hollowed out\" from the inside.\n",
    "| Variable Name | Logic / Interaction | Forensic \"Red Flag\" Utility |\n",
    "|---------------|---------------------|------------------------------|\n",
    "| sig_ghost_labor | Δ_discharges < 0 & Δ_salaries > 0 | Insider Extraction Signal: Patient volume is falling while payroll expands. Indicates managerial insulation or failure to adjust staffing to clinical demand. |\n",
    "| sig_supply_starvation | Δ_med_supplies < 0 & Δ_admin_load >= 0 | Quality Compression Indicator: Clinical supply spending falls while administrative burden remains stable or rises, suggesting bedside cost cutting to protect overhead. |\n",
    "| sig_revenue_mirage | Δ_gross_rev > 0 & Δ_coll_eff < 0 | Revenue Inflation Flag: Gross charges rise while collection efficiency declines, indicating pricing inflation masking revenue cycle deterioration. |\n",
    "| sig_collection_collapse | Δ_ar_velocity > 5 & Δ_days_cash < 0 | Cash Conversion Breakdown: Accounts receivable aging accelerates while liquidity declines, signaling uncollectible revenue and near-term financial strain. |\n",
    "| sig_capital_flight | Δ_capex < 0 & Δ_cap_age > 0.02 | Capital Withdrawal Pattern: Investment halts while infrastructure ages, consistent with asset harvesting prior to restructuring or closure. |\n",
    "| sig_liquidity_squeeze | Δ_days_cash < 0 & Δ_ap_lag > 0 | Vendor Payment Pressure: Cash declines while payment delays increase, indicating reliance on supplier credit to survive. |\n",
    "| siphon_ratio | HomeOfficeAdj / NetEquity | Related-Party Extraction Ratio: Measures magnitude of parent-level allocations relative to equity, highlighting potential resource diversion. |\n",
    "| subsidy_intensity | (DSH + IME) / NetRevenue | Federal Dependence Ratio: Identifies high reliance on subsidy streams, increasing vulnerability to reimbursement or audit shifts. |\n",
    "\n",
    "🏘️ Category 10: Market Context & Relative Performance\n",
    "These variables are \"Z-Score\" style features. They normalize a hospital's performance against its Peer Group (State, Bed Size, and Control Type) to identify true outliers.\n",
    "| Variable Name | Logic / Peer Comparison | Forensic \"Relative\" Utility |\n",
    "|---------------|------------------------|-----------------------------|\n",
    "| rel_operating_margin | Hospital_Margin / State_Median_Margin | Local Market Context: Evaluates performance relative to state peers. A materially lower ratio in a strong-margin state signals institution-specific dysfunction rather than systemic pressure. |\n",
    "| market_share_delta | Δ(Hosp_Discharges / County_Total_Discharges) | Competitive Erosion Indicator: Measures loss of patient volume relative to local competitors, signaling declining market relevance. |\n",
    "| wage_index_tension | Hosp_Avg_Salary / State_Avg_Salary | Labor Cost Imbalance: Elevated ratios indicate above-market wage pressure, often driven by contract labor or retention instability. |\n",
    "| dsh_concentration_index | Hosp_DSH_Payment / Peer_Avg_DSH | Safety-Net Concentration: Identifies disproportionate burden of uninsured care relative to local peers. |\n",
    "| occupancy_rate | Total_Patient_Days / (Licensed_Beds * 365) | Capacity Utilization Metric: Persistent low occupancy combined with high fixed costs creates structural inefficiency risk. |\n",
    "| outpatient_revenue_mix | Outpatient_Rev / Total_Patient_Rev | Strategic Positioning Signal: Evaluates alignment with regional outpatient trends; lagging transition increases inpatient dependency risk. |\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n"
   ]
