   "source": [
    "# NOTE for Extraction\n",
    "\n",
    "### Medicare Cost Report Data Extraction and Validation\n",
    "\n",
    "The Medicare Cost Report panel used in this analysis was constructed from the CMS **HOSP10 cost report extracts**. Because the CMS extracts vary across years and contain irregular formatting, a defensive extraction and validation pipeline was implemented.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 1. Raw Data Ingestion\n",
    "\n",
    "- Cost report extracts were loaded **year-by-year** (e.g., `HOSP10FY2011`–`HOSP10FY2023`).\n",
    "- The primary source files include:\n",
    "  - **RPT files** containing provider identifiers and report metadata.\n",
    "  - **NMRC files** containing numeric worksheet values.\n",
    "  - **ALPHA files** containing text worksheet values.\n",
    "- Files were read defensively with delimiter sniffing and relaxed parsing to accommodate irregular column structures and occasional formatting inconsistencies.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 2. Worksheet Address Mapping\n",
    "\n",
    "Cost report variables are not stored as named fields. Instead, they are located by:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Worksheet code**\n",
    "- **Line number**\n",
    "- **Column number**\n",
    "\n",
    "To ensure correct extraction:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Automated **sniffing routines** scanned candidate worksheet locations.\n",
    "- Potential addresses were evaluated using:\n",
    "  - observation counts\n",
    "  - value plausibility\n",
    "  - consistency across years\n",
    "- The most stable and populated addresses were selected for each variable.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 3. Cross-Year Schema Stabilization\n",
    "\n",
    "CMS worksheet layouts can shift between reporting years.  \n",
    "To maintain consistency across the panel:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Variable locations were validated **year-by-year**.\n",
    "- A dynamic mapping matrix was constructed to track address changes.\n",
    "- This prevents silent extraction errors that occur when a fixed schema is assumed.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 4. Panel Construction\n",
    "\n",
    "The validated worksheet values were merged with provider identifiers from the RPT files to create a unified **facility-year panel dataset**.\n",
    "\n",
    "Each observation represents a **hospital cost report filing for a given year**.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 5. Derived Structural Variables\n",
    "\n",
    "After extraction, additional variables were created to support forensic and anomaly analysis:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Financial ratios (e.g., revenue per day, assets per bed)\n",
    "- Operating margin measures\n",
    "- Temporal change indicators\n",
    "- Peer grouping and reporting regime labels\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 6. Data Quality Assurance\n",
    "\n",
    "Multiple safeguards were implemented to ensure reliability:\n",
    "\n",
    "- robust parsing to handle formatting anomalies\n",
    "- cross-year consistency checks\n",
    "- population and plausibility screening for extracted variables\n",
    "- validation of observation counts across reporting years\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "This extraction framework ensures that the resulting dataset reflects a **consistent longitudinal panel of Medicare hospital cost reports**, while accounting for known schema changes and formatting irregularities in the CMS source files.\n",
    "\n",
    "###  Data Entry Errors\n",
    "Raw CMS cost report data contains known data entry errors and that implausible values were capped at physically defensible upper bounds prior to analysis.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Peer Group Assignment (Ownership + Size + Teaching/GME + Market Context)\n",
    "\n",
    "Hospital cost reports exhibit strong structural differences driven by **ownership**, **scale**, and **teaching activity**.  \n",
    "To avoid comparing fundamentally different institutions (e.g., a small rural CAH vs. a large urban academic medical center), each facility-year observation is assigned to a **peer group** representing hospitals with broadly similar operating conditions.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 1. Core Dimensions Used for Peer Grouping\n",
    "\n",
    "Peer groups are constructed using a combination of:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Ownership / control type** (e.g., government, nonprofit, for-profit), derived from CMS ownership/control codes.\n",
    "- **Size / scale**, proxied by structural capacity measures (e.g., licensed beds and/or patient volume).  \n",
    "  Size is discretized into bins (for example, small/medium/large) to create comparability sets.\n",
    "- **Teaching intensity (GME)**, capturing academic medical center activity and residency training footprint.  \n",
    "  Teaching status is defined using cost report indicators and/or GME-related fields (for example, direct/indirect GME signals when available), and then grouped into categories such as non-teaching vs. teaching (or low/medium/high teaching intensity).\n",
    "- **Geographic/market context** (e.g., state or region), used to ensure peer comparisons reflect local labor costs, payer mix, and market structure.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 2. Two Peer Resolutions\n",
    "\n",
    "This study uses two levels of peer grouping:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **`peer_group` (coarse peers):**  \n",
    "  A broader grouping intended for stable benchmarking (ownership × size × teaching), minimizing sparsity while preserving key structural differences.\n",
    "- **`peer_group_fine` (fine peers):**  \n",
    "  A narrower grouping that adds additional stratification (such as geography and/or tighter size/teaching bins) for analyses that benefit from more local comparators (for example, year-specific digit tests or tight relational benchmarking).\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 3. Why Peer Groups Matter for Anomaly Detection\n",
    "\n",
    "Peer grouping is a structural normalization layer used throughout the forensic models:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Peer groups define the comparison population for **robust z-scores** of performance measures.\n",
    "- Multivariate relational anomalies (e.g., robust Mahalanobis distance) are estimated **within peer groups** to avoid mixing distinct covariance structures.\n",
    "- Year-specific peer strata support detection of gaming signatures that are only meaningful relative to comparable institutions (e.g., bunching near thresholds, coordinated improvements).\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 4. Practical Interpretation\n",
    "\n",
    "A peer group should be read as:  \n",
    "> “Hospitals with similar governance incentives, similar operating scale, and similar teaching/GME footprint (and, when relevant, similar geographic market context).”\n",
    "\n",
    "This ensures that anomaly signals reflect unusual behavior **within an appropriate comparison set**, rather than predictable differences across hospital types.\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
