   "source": [
    "# 5. Train / Validation\n",
    "\n",
    "### Training–Inference Separation for Feature Scaling\n",
    "\n",
    "To prevent information leakage and ensure reproducible model inputs, feature scaling and transformation parameters are estimated using a strict **training–inference separation framework**.\n",
    "\n",
    "The hospital panel is first divided into two subsets based on the `data_regime` variable:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Baseline training panel (2012–2018):** used to estimate all feature transformations and scaling parameters.\n",
    "- **Scoring panel (all other years):** transformed using the previously estimated parameters but **never used to fit them**.\n",
    "\n",
    "The workflow proceeds as follows:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Training phase**\n",
    "   - Observations labeled `baseline` are extracted into a training dataset.\n",
    "   - The function `build_model_features(..., fit=True)` computes all engineered features and fits the scaling transformations.\n",
    "   - The resulting scaler parameters (medians, IQR values, and percentile mappings) are saved to disk for later reuse.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. **Inference phase**\n",
    "   - The scalers are reloaded from disk.\n",
    "   - All non-baseline observations are processed using `build_model_features(..., fit=False)`, which applies the **frozen training scalers** without updating them.\n",
    "\n",
    "3. **Panel reconstruction**\n",
    "   - The scaled training and scoring panels are recombined and sorted by hospital identifier (`PRVDR_NUM`) and fiscal-year start date (`FY_BGN_DT`) to restore the full longitudinal structure of the dataset.\n",
    "\n",
    "This approach ensures that feature scaling reflects only historical baseline behavior, preventing future observations from influencing the normalization of earlier data. As a result, all anomaly detection models operate under conditions that mirror true out-of-sample prediction."
   ]
  },
