    "### Anomaly Detection Framework\n",
    "\n",
    "This analysis uses a **multi-layer forensic detection system** designed to identify anomalous financial reporting behavior in Medicare Cost Reports.  \n",
    "The framework integrates **structural, behavioral, and temporal signals**.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1. Structural Anomaly Detection (VAE)\n",
    "\n",
    "Structural irregularities in financial reporting are detected using a **Variational Autoencoder (VAE)**.\n",
    "\n",
    "- The VAE is trained on baseline hospital reporting patterns.\n",
    "- It learns the **normal multivariate structure** of financial variables.\n",
    "- **Reconstruction error** is used as a structural anomaly score.\n",
    "- High scores indicate **unusual accounting geometry or reporting structure**.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2. Behavioral Gaming Detection (SRRI)\n",
    "\n",
    "Strategic reporting behavior is captured through a **Strategic Reporting Risk Index (SRRI)** composed of multiple forensic indicators.\n",
    "\n",
    "Key indicators include:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Threshold bunching** near regulatory performance cutoffs.\n",
    "- **Coordinated improvements** across multiple performance metrics.\n",
    "- **Residual acceleration** relative to historical performance baselines.\n",
    "- **Cross-metric consistency patterns** suggesting engineered outcomes.\n",
    "- **Volatility suppression** inconsistent with normal operational variation.\n",
    "\n",
    "These signals are aggregated to form a **behavioral gaming score**.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### 3. Statistical Shock Detection (Isolation Forest)\n",
    "\n",
    "Sudden disruptions in reporting dynamics are identified using an **Isolation Forest**.\n",
    "\n",
    "- Applied to **panel-derived financial trajectories**.\n",
    "- Detects **temporal discontinuities and regime breaks**.\n",
    "- Captures unusual shifts **not explained by normal variation**.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### 4. Score Normalization and Fusion\n",
    "\n",
    "To ensure comparability across heterogeneous anomaly signals:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Each anomaly score is converted to an **industry-wide percentile rank**.\n",
    "- Percentiles preserve the **relative extremity** of observations while removing scale differences.\n",
    "\n",
    "The normalized signals are combined into a **fused risk score**:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "Risk_{fused} =\n",
    "0.4 \\cdot Structural +\n",
    "0.4 \\cdot Behavioral +\n",
    "0.2 \\cdot Shock\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Structural** = VAE anomaly percentile  \n",
    "- **Behavioral** = SRRI percentile  \n",
    "- **Shock** = Isolation Forest percentile\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### 5. Risk Classification\n",
    "\n",
    "Facility-year observations are classified into interpretable anomaly categories using **90th percentile thresholds** for each signal.\n",
    "\n",
    "An observation is flagged when it exceeds the top 10% of the industry distribution for a given detector.\n",
    "\n",
    "This produces a taxonomy of reporting risk:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **No major anomaly detected**\n",
    "- **Structural accounting irregularity**\n",
    "- **Behavioral gaming signature**\n",
    "- **Statistical shock event**\n",
    "- **Two-domain anomaly combinations**\n",
    "- **Critical multi-dimensional anomaly** (all three signals)\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "This framework provides both **granular anomaly detection** and **decision-support-friendly classification** across the national panel of hospital cost reports."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "55fb8914-39ef-4e1e-b884-2d69169a2f0c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 6.  Fused Risk Score Construction\n",
    "\n",
    "To synthesize multiple anomaly detection signals into a single interpretable indicator, we construct a **fused reporting risk score** that integrates structural, behavioral, and statistical shock signals.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 1. Motivation\n",
    "\n",
    "Each anomaly detector captures a different dimension of reporting irregularity:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Structural anomalies (VAE):** multivariate deviations in financial reporting structure.\n",
    "- **Behavioral anomalies (SRRI):** strategic reporting patterns such as bunching, coordinated improvements, and volatility suppression.\n",
    "- **Statistical shock anomalies (Isolation Forest):** abrupt temporal discontinuities in panel financial dynamics.\n",
    "\n",
    "Because these signals arise from distinct mechanisms, combining them produces a more robust indicator of reporting risk than relying on any single detector.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 2. Percentile Normalization\n",
    "\n",
    "The raw anomaly scores produced by each method exist on different numerical scales.  \n",
    "To ensure comparability, each score is converted to an **industry-wide percentile rank**:\n",
    "\n",
    "- VAE structural anomaly score → `vae_pct`\n",
    "- Strategic Reporting Risk Index → `srri_pct`\n",
    "- Isolation Forest anomaly score → `if_pct`\n",
    "\n",
    "Percentile normalization preserves the relative extremity of each observation while removing scale dependence and distributional assumptions.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 3. Fused Risk Score\n",
    "\n",
    "The normalized signals are combined using a weighted average:\n",
    "\n",
    "\\[\n",
    "Risk_{fused} =\n",
    "0.4 \\times Structural +\n",
    "0.4 \\times Behavioral +\n",
    "0.2 \\times Shock\n",
    "\\]\n",
    "\n",
    "where:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Structural = `vae_pct`**\n",
    "- **Behavioral = `srri_pct`**\n",
    "- **Shock = `if_pct`**\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 4. Weighting Rationale\n",
    "\n",
    "Weights reflect the relative stability and interpretability of each signal:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Structural and behavioral anomalies receive higher weights (0.4 each) because they capture **persistent reporting patterns**.\n",
    "- Shock anomalies receive a lower weight (0.2) because **sudden statistical breaks may arise from legitimate operational events** (e.g., mergers, reporting adjustments, or systemic disruptions such as COVID).\n",
    "\n",
    "This weighting scheme balances persistent irregularities against transient shocks.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 5. Interpretation\n",
    "\n",
    "The fused score can be interpreted as a **consensus anomaly measure** across independent detectors.  \n",
    "Higher values indicate facility-years exhibiting stronger evidence of anomalous reporting behavior across multiple analytical dimensions.\n",
    "\n",
    "This ensemble approach improves robustness and reduces the risk that a single detector dominates the anomaly assessment."
   ]
  },
