   "source": [
    "# 14. Crosstabs with Financial Liquidity\n",
    "\n",
    "### Liquidity Profile Across Anomaly Risk Categories\n",
    "\n",
    "The distribution of liquidity across anomaly risk categories reveals economically meaningful patterns consistent with known hospital financial dynamics. Facilities with **No Major Anomaly Detected** overwhelmingly fall into the **Very Strong liquidity bucket (84.5%)**, indicating that financially stable hospitals rarely exhibit anomalous reporting behavior. In contrast, categories associated with **structural accounting irregularities** and **statistical shock events** show substantially higher shares of hospitals in **critical liquidity distress**, suggesting that reporting irregularities and abrupt financial shifts often occur in environments of financial pressure. The **Statistical Shock Event** category exhibits the highest concentration of critical liquidity (20.1%), consistent with the interpretation that sharp panel discontinuities frequently arise during periods of operational or financial disruption. Hybrid categories combining behavioral or structural signals with shock dynamics fall between these extremes, reflecting a mixture of distressed institutions and organizations adjusting reporting practices during turbulent periods. Notably, even the most severe anomaly class still contains a substantial proportion of hospitals with strong liquidity, indicating that some detected patterns may reflect **strategic financial management or reporting optimization rather than pure financial distress**. Overall, the liquidity distribution aligns with expectations: financially stable hospitals cluster in strong liquidity regimes, while anomaly signals become progressively more common as liquidity conditions deteriorate."
   ]
